---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Plain Theory Labs builds infrastructure engines that turn scheduler exports and telemetry into traceable, policy-ready recommendations — with explicit assumptions and measurable outcomes.";

const observations = [
  ["jobs_analyzed", "73,367"],
  ["average_efficiency_score", "25.74%"],
  ["risk_flag_jobs", "65,614"],
  ["pct_short_jobs_lt_1m", "40.95%"],
  ["pct_util_zero", "33.27%"],
  ["median_util_avg", "16.00%"]
] as const;

const excerpt = `engine: ACE v0.1
mode: msa
jobs_analyzed: 73,367
average_efficiency_score: 25.74%
risk_flag_jobs: 65,614
review_queue_a: near_zero_util
review_queue_b: over_requested
review_queue_c: runtime_variance
capacity_savings_usd: computed per run
impact_model: electricity, carbon, water`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>Plain Theory Labs</h1>
    <p class="thesis">Infrastructure engines for intelligent, sustainable compute.</p>

    <p>
      We are researchers, engineers, and scientists building engines that turn raw scheduler exports and telemetry
      into traceable, policy-ready guidance — recommendations you can simulate, verify, and defend with explicit
      assumptions and measurable outcomes.
    </p>

    <p>
      AI workloads are accelerating demand across every layer of the stack: power draw, cooling capacity, water
      consumption, GPU supply, and operational cost. Most organizations can already see dashboards and logs. What
      they cannot do is connect that telemetry to decisions — what to change, what to enforce, and what tradeoffs
      are actually acceptable given their constraints.
    </p>

    <p>
      We build the decision layer: engines that score workload behavior, surface review candidates, model operational
      impact across energy and carbon, and produce outputs that operators, researchers, and institutional
      stakeholders can read, challenge, and adopt as standards.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/ace">ACE Engine &rarr;</a>
      <span class="muted">Our first-generation allocation and cost engine.</span>
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The problem is auditability</h2>

    <p>
      Utilization charts are everywhere. Actionable decisions are not. The gap between raw telemetry and a
      defensible recommendation is wider than it looks — especially when the recommendation needs to hold up
      across operators, procurement, sustainability reporting, and institutional review.
    </p>

    <p>
      Common failure modes: recommendations that cannot be traced back to specific jobs or measurement windows,
      impact estimates built on undisclosed assumptions, and no mechanism to compare results across runs or
      configurations. You cannot improve what you cannot explain.
    </p>

    <p>
      Our engines make assumptions explicit, link every recommendation to source records, and produce structured
      outputs designed for review — not just consumption.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>What the data actually shows</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Single institutional trace. MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset, converted to ACE canonical schema.
      Numbers are real. Interpretation depends on telemetry quality, workload mix, and how utilization is measured.
    </p>

    <div class="panel">
      <pre class="report-excerpt"><code>{excerpt}</code></pre>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Metric</th>
            <th>Value</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {observations.map(([metric, value]) => (
            <tr>
              <td><code>{metric}</code></td>
              <td>{value}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      40.95% of jobs ran under one minute. Short jobs dominate scheduling overhead and disappear in broad
      utilization averages — the average looks better than the workload actually is.
    </p>

    <p>
      33.27% of jobs show near-zero GPU utilization. Together with a median utilization average of 16%, this
      points to a mix of over-requesting, idle allocation, missing telemetry, and workload mismatch. Each
      category has different operational causes and different appropriate responses.
    </p>

    <p>
      65,614 jobs were flagged for review across three queues: near-zero utilization, over-requested resources,
      and runtime variance. Review queues are not enforcement — they are structured inputs for human decisions.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>How we work</h2>

    <p>
      We start from exported records — <code>sacct</code> output, scheduler logs, DCGM telemetry, CSV traces —
      and convert them into a canonical schema with explicit provenance. From there, ACE scores each job,
      applies safety controls that block unsafe downsizing recommendations, models impact across electricity,
      carbon, and water, and writes structured JSON and human-readable HTML that you can version, diff, and share.
    </p>

    <p>
      No agent access to production schedulers. No enforcement. No changes to running systems. Every output is
      traceable to source records and every assumption is documented so you can replace them with your own.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Open by default</h2>

    <p>
      Scientific progress is collective. We publish methods, schemas, and write-ups when it is safe to share,
      with a focus on reproducibility and clear assumptions so others can inspect, challenge, and improve the work.
      Validation against public datasets is a first principle, not an afterthought.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links"><a href="/contact">Work with us &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
